We recommended that Management:

Create an organizational structure which will outline the flow of activities and define the roles and responsibilities of the personnel assigned in the waterworks system and to require the designated General Manager or Head of Office, with the assistance of the Municipal Engineer, MPDC, Municipal Treasurer and Municipal Accountant, to formulate written policies and procedures in the operation of the water system;

Direct the Municipal Treasurer and the Municipal Accountant to require in writing the system developer to install security controls which will require prior authorization of personnel before performing actions that will cancel and delete previous transactions and reprint an OR and to complete the customization that will generate reliable reports.

We recommended that Management:
Instruct the Municipal Accountant to:
Adopt the moving average method for costing inventories;
Record the procurement of semi-expendable properties to proper asset account following the perpetual inventory method;
Require the Supply Officer to:
Conduct periodic physical inventory of supplies every semester and prepare and submit RPCI to the Audit Team using the prescribed template in Annex 48 of the MNGAS for LGUs;
Consolidate weekly the issuances of RIS using SSMI and submit the same with original copy of RIS to the Municipal Accountant as basis for preparation of JEV in the recording of expenditure;
Prepare and maintain the required forms, registries and reports for semi-expendable properties and assign a separate ICS control number for low-valued items and high-valued items to strengthen the controls and safeguards over the semi-expendable properties;
Conduct annual physical count of semi-expendable properties and prepare the RPCSP;
Direct the Municipal Accountant and Supply Officer to:
Reconcile the noted discrepancies in the recording of receipts and issuances of the Office Supplies Inventory; and
Maintain complete SLCs and Stock Cards, respectively, for each item of the inventory account and conduct regular reconciliation of their inventory records.

We recommended that Management:
Direct the GSO and the Municipal Accountant to conduct regular monitoring and updating of property and accounting records for reconciliation;
Direct the Head of the Inventory Committee to complete the conduct of physical count of all PPE, prepare the inventory report and facilitate the reconciliation of the result of the inventory count with property and accounting records;
Require the Municipal Accountant to effect the necessary adjustments on the overstatement of assets and equity in the net amount of ₱803,454.15 due to various accounting errors; and
Instruct the Municipal Accountant and GSO to coordinate and initiate compliance with the implementation of the one-time cleansing of PPE accounts in order to come up with a reliable balance of the PPE accounts.

We recommended that Management:
Require the Municipal Accountant to:
Adjust the balances of PS, MOOE, and CO in the Current Appropriation in the Final Budget consistent with the supplemental budgets to present the accurate balances of appropriations in the financial statements;
Adjust the beginning balance of the Continuing Appropriation in CY 2024 under the Education Program by ₱1,050,196.72 to reflect the correct ending balance in CY 2023;
Analyze the transactions affecting the balance of Continuing Appropriation and make the necessary adjustments on the discrepancy between the ending balance in CY 2023 and forwarded balance in CY 2024 in the net amount of ₱1,160,507.10; and
Direct the Municipal Budget Officer to reprogram the unexpended balance of appropriation for MOOE under the 20 percent DF amounting to ₱3,624,148.20 for the programs, projects and activities under the CO of the same fund.

We recommended that Management:
Instruct the BAC and BAC Secretariat to ensure consistency in dates and information across all bidding documents to maintain accuracy and avoid discrepancies;
Direct the BAC Secretariat to publish the NOA and NTP in the PhilGEPS within the prescribed period;
Instruct the Municipal Treasurer to ensure that the Delivery Receipt and Sales Invoice are duly dated; and
Require the Municipal Accountant, in coordination with the BAC Secretariat, to submit the lacking documents to support claims and for review and evaluation of the Audit Team.

We recommended that Management:

Require the BAC Secretariat to ensure that the required PhilGEPS posting of NOA, NTP and contracts be strictly observed;



Direct the BAC to require the suppliers to submit the mandatory documents in the use of alternative method of Small Value Procurement;



Require the supply officer to ensure that the AIR is duly accomplished and indicate in the “Acceptance” portion of the AIR the date of acceptance and put a check () mark whether the delivery is complete or partial as to quantity and the inspection officer to indicate in the “Inspection” portion of the AIR the date of inspection and put a check () mark indicating that he has inspected, verified and found in order the items delivered as to quantity and specifications; and

Instruct the Municipal Accountant to submit the lacking documents for further evaluation of the Audit Team and to ensure that all documentary requirements are duly signed and complete for transparency and propriety of the transactions.

We recommended that Management:

Instruct the BAC to invite representatives from National Associations of Contractors duly recognized by the Construction Industry Authority of the Philippines as observer in all stages of the procurement of infrastructure projects and to require the BAC, with the assistance of the BAC Secretariat and TWG, to verify the list of contractor’s equipment together with its availability and operating condition to ensure availability of required equipment during the contract period;

d. Require the Municipal Accountant, with the assistance of the BAC Secretariat and the Municipal Engineer, to submit the aforementioned lacking documents for further evaluation of the Audit Team.

