We recommended that Management:

a.	Create an organizational structure which will outline the flow of activities and define the roles and responsibilities of the personnel assigned in the waterworks system. After which, require the designated General Manager or Head of Office, with the assistance of the Municipal Engineer, MPDC, Municipal Treasurer and Municipal Accountant, to formulate written policies and procedures in the operation of the water system;

b.	Direct the Municipal Treasurer and the Municipal Accountant to require in writing the system developer to provide the LGU with the computer system user’s manual and to install system controls which will require prior authorization to the personnel before performing actions that will undo previous transactions or adjust, change or delete records and will require the collector to indicate his username and specific password to log in into the system;  

c.	Require the personnel assigned in billing section to maintain duplicate copy of billing statements/ statement of accounts, to indicate the reason for bill adjustments in the Billing Adjustment Memo, to make a written report on the cause/s of discrepancy between the outstanding balance of concessionaires in the statement of account and the general ledger and to incorporate therein the suggested corrective measures and to provide a copy of the written report to the Audit Team for further evaluation; and

d. Oblige the LGU personnel to pay their water bills on time and require the collectors to collect the penalty accruing to delinquent concessionaires, except those that are covered by the Waiver and Authorization agreement.

We recommended that Management: 


a. 	Require the Municipal Solid Waste Management Board (MSWMB) to strictly implement the specific provisions of Municipal Ordinance No. 2004-02 dated February 4, 2004, otherwise known as the “Comprehensive Solid Waste Management Ordinance of the Municipality” on waste segregation, collection, disposal and imposition of fines and penalties against persons committing the prohibited acts provided in Section 48 of RA No. 9003 to achieve the targets projected in the 10-year Solid Waste Management Plan geared towards fulfilling the commitment of Management to protect, preserve and conserve the ecosystem and its inhabitants;

b. 	Instruct the MPDC to include the procurement of the necessary equipment and facilities as PPAs under the MDF and to monitor the implementation of the PPAs intended for the Sanitary Landfill under the MDF especially those that are essential in transporting, spreading and compacting solid wastes and grading the covered surfaces to minimize loose layers and maximize the space in the landfill;

c. 	Require the OIC Human Resource and Management Officer (HRMO) to assign qualified personnel occupying permanent position in the operations of the Sanitary Landfill who shall ensure proper handling of solid wastes in accordance with the guidelines pursuant to RA No. 9003; and

d. 	Direct the MSWMB to comply with the minimum criteria in the establishment and operation of Sanitary Landfill provided in Sections 41 and 42 of RA No. 9003 to maximize the use of Sanitary Landfill and ensure the protection of personnel, public health and environment.

We recommended that Management:
Require the Bids and Awards Committee (BAC) to verify carefully the SLCC submitted by the bidders to ensure that the project indicated therein is similar to the contract to be bid, and whose value, adjusted to current prices using the PSA consumer price indices is at least 50 percent of the ABC to ensure that the LGU is contracting with an entity who has already accomplished one project and thus is capable of completing the project at hand;
Require the BAC Secretariat to clearly address the Invitations sent to the duly recognized private group and to issue the NTP together with a copy of the approved contract to the successful bidder within seven cds from the date of approval of the contract;
Require the Technical Working Group (TWG) to ensure that post-qualification should be completed within 12 cds after determination of LCB;
Require the BAC, in coordination with the TWG Members, to include in the Post-Qualification Evaluation Report the actions taken in the verification of delay in the partial delivery of goods in the ongoing contract of the bidder, failure to deliver or perform any or all of the goods or services within the period(s) specified in the contract and unsatisfactory performance of the supplier's obligation in order ensure the qualification of the bidder; and
Require the Municipal Accountant, with the assistance of the BAC Secretariat, to submit the lacking documents for further evaluation of the Audit Team.

